text:
50 Watts Street, north side, west of Sullivan Street. This little house and the one adjoining it on the right will be replaced before 1920 by a Ford service station.
1912.

Gift of Samuel Landsman.

42-46 Watts Street, at, adjoining and west of the N.W. corner of Sullivan Street. Also shown is Sullivan Street (Nos. 46-56) west side, north from Watts to but not including Broome Streets. Frame building shown at the corner bears two numbers; 42 Watts Street and 46 Sullivan Street. Other frame houses shown are 46 Watts and 50-52 Sullivan Street.

About 1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Sullivan Street, east side, south from Watts Street to the southern end of Sullivan Street at Canal Street. All of the buildings shown on the east side of Sullivan Street are shortly to be razed, and the west side of Sullivan Street, from Grand to Canal Streets, inclusive, will become part of the west side of Sixth Avenue. 1926.

Sullivan Street, east side, south from Watts Street to the southern end of Sullivan Street at Canal Street. All of the buildings shown on the east side of Sullivan Street are shortly to be razed, and the west side of Sullivan Street, from Grand to Canal Streets, inclusive, will become part of the west side of Sixth Avenue. 1926.

Watts Street, easternmost block, east from Sullivan Street (future Sixth Avenue Extension). Between Thompson Street and West Broadway there is a triangular plaza where Watts and Broome Streets fuse. The south side of this plaza now has Broome Street house numbers, although originally it must have held the first six odd numbers on Watts Street.
The entire south side of Watts Street from Sullivan to Thompson Streets is about to be demolished in the process of building the new subway and extending Sixth Avenue southward.
1926.

Watts Street, west from Sullivan Street and including the future Sixth Avenue Extension. 42 Watts Street, the frame house with the brick facing on the 46tSullivan Street side, is one of the buildings which will have to be demolished. Nos. 53,55 Watts Street, on the south side, between the loft building, and the three 5-story tenement houses, are also brick-faced frames. 1926.

(1)
Sixth Avenue, west side, north from and including Watts Street, along the line of and including the former Clark Street, which has been absorbed by Sixth Avenue. No. 46 Watts Street, which used to be two doors from the N.W. corner of Sullivan and Watts Streets, is now practically at the N.W. corner of Sixth Avenue.
1932.

J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.

(2)
The same during the extension of Sixth Ave. Note the political banners upon the fire escapes of No. 46. They depict the Democratic presidential candidates, Alfred E. Smith and William T. Robinson.

October 19, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

Sixth Avenue and Sullivan Street, north from Broome Street. The former is thru the center and the Butterick Building fronts on same at Spring Street. This structure bears No. 161 Sixth Avenue. Buildings at the left are included with this thoroughfare tho previously they faced on the now obliterated Clark Street. To the right appears an extensive view up Sullivan Street. The C.G. text:
53 to 61 Watts Street, south side, between Sixth Ave. Extension and Varick Street, showing three 5-story tenements (Nos. 57-61) under demolition. These adjoin the 10-story structure (extreme right) at the S.E. corner of this street and Varick Street. The two 3-story buildings are frame construction with brick fronts and are east of the latter.

October 18, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
